<A NAME = "15"></A>Copyright
NEW TECHNOLOGY WEEK via NewsNet
April 23, 1990

ASME TO SCREEN COUNTERFEITS

Counterfeit and substandard screws, bolts, washers and other
fasteners will have a harder time making it into U.S. markets
thanks to the newly initiated American Society of Mechanical
Engineers' fastner accreditation program (FAP).  "In many
instances, suppliers provided bogus quality certifications and
other misrepresentations to their buyers," says SME. This has
lead to millions of counterfeit fasteners with have cracked,
sheared or otherwise failed in helicopters, trucks, bridges,
nuclear power plants, coal mines, tanks and other military
equipment.

SME hopes that the accreditation program will help government
efforts in stemming the flow of counterfeit goods by subjecting
would-be fastener suppliers to stringent reviews. Until now, the
Defense Department and aerospace industry had no way of
determining whether or not they were dealing with a supplier
capable of producing high strength, high quality and safe
fastener products, says ASME.




